rComments: I took health, aging, and the lifecycle and loved the course, mainly because the Professor made it so interesting. She was certainly one of the best Professors I have ever had.
I took 2 health courses with Walsh and both times I received an A. If you go to class and take good notes on both the material and her CURRENT EVENTS, you can definitely get over an 80 in the course!
Caring, approachable, passionate about material. Exams tough but fair.
Professor Walsh cares a lot about her students and tries really hard to make sure that they understand the course material.  This was by far one of my best courses.

The worst professor ever. Rather than focus on useful course material she will ask completely unnecessary questions on your midterm/final such as On this day (date) we watched a clip what was it about? Basically to make sure you actually went to class. Also extremely preachy and kind of crazy making students move around during exams.
She is passionate about health care and her lectures are terrific.
Stimulating lectures.  No knowledge yet about her exams, since she didn't draft the midterm and just took  over teaching the course.

Biased views and is not open to discussion/opposing ideas. A lot of pointless rules. Struggles with the use of technology; highly unorganized in presenta/tion of material. Exams focus on memorization of tedious detail rather than understanding of material. On the up side, as long as you read the text and memorize her lectures, very easy.
Amazing lecturer. Very interesting and easy to follow.
Amazing professor.  Extremely helpful.  She is passionate about health care and really tries hard to make the material extremely interesting.
Material is very interesting. Great lectures.  I would definitely recommend this course.
Best class by far!
The best professor I have ever had.  She is passionate about health care and tries so hard to engage students

I find her lectures extremely biased (left-winged) and while she has the best intentions at heart, her views are often narrow-minded and partisan. She is also very disorganized when it comes to the format of her lectures and her notes. The assignment is too general and she takes forever to post up the midterm marks, which was all MC. Horrible prof.

Her lectures are ok, but she tends to read out of the textbook more than adding insight or explanation to what is in the textbook. Very strict in terms of rules in her class ,some of which are highly unneccessary. Lastly, being a lawyer she brings the legal perspective into class, at times its appropriate and at other times its in bad taste.
She's very interested in what she teaches. She tends to advocate a lot. She can make exams tricky but she's likes to be asked questions.

The assignment was straightforward, and if you take careful consideration of what your TA expects, you'll do good on it. The exams however were very tricky. The midterm average was 72 so she explicity said she would have to make the final harder, and boy did she ever! It's not hard to get 70's, but getting 80's (forget 90's) is another story.

a nice person. her assignments are easy but very general, you can approach it in soo many ways (not a good thing). mid-terms are easy and finals are hard. it's all application of material and knowing symptoms of diseases. she's very approachable ands loves for students to speak in her class, try to engage yourself in her class.
she is amazing and she really loves what she is doing, really inspiring and she's really helpful..always trying to help students..

She is more than a professor. She has inspired me to take more courses in health. For exams, you need to read the reader prior to lectures and attend tutorials every week, then exams are easy. Otherwise, good luck!
